examples/welcome.dx.sourceText:
::heading level=1 id=doc-hero
Welcome to DOC DB
::end

::quote id=hero-tagline
Structured docs that agents can query, humans can edit, and both can trust.
::end

::heading level=2 id=workspace-overview class=section-heading
What This Workspace Is
::end

::paragraph id=workspace-description
DOC DB is a writing environment where every document lives in SQLite. Your words are structured as typed blocks - headings, paragraphs, lists, code, quotes - and that structure is what makes them fast to search, easy to style, and safe for automated edits.
::end

::heading level=2 id=what-you-build class=section-heading
What You Can Build Here
::end

::bulleted-list id=capability-list
Write documents as block-structured source that parses into clean, typed data
Query docs by title, tag, or full-text search from any MCP-connected agent
Style individual blocks with scoped ids and classes - no global overrides
Preview changes instantly in the webview while source stays in version control
::end

::heading level=2 id=authoring-rules class=section-heading
Writing Standard
::end

::numbered-list id=rules-list
Open every document with a single H1 that names the content exactly.
Add one concise purpose sentence directly after the heading.
Use H2 for workflow phases, decisions, or reference groupings.
Prefer lists over dense paragraphs whenever steps or options are involved.
Assign ids/classes to blocks you intend to target in scoped CSS editing.
::end

::heading level=2 id=design-reference class=section-heading
Design Tokens in Action
::end

::paragraph id=token-note
CSS blocks are stored as document content and are NOT globally auto-applied in rendered mode. CSS is only activated through selector-scoped editing flows.
::end

